[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[screaming] &gt;&gt; Hey yo, I live under the bridge eating [music] rocks for fun. Got a YouTube channel and I just hit one. So subscribe just [music] mad comments saying stop, but I keep on posting from the top of my'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rock. &gt;&gt; Laleria is the latest AI music model coming out from Google and it\'s the first of several AI music models that we\'re going to be adding over on the OpenArt platform. And if you\'ve never worked with Laleria before, I want to'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'take a few minutes to show you how it\'s different from other AI music generators. And also show you a couple of things it does differently than some of the other models you may have tried. I\'m going to give you two links to the description, both of which are designed to help you write prompts better for this model. I\'m going to show you'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'examples of all of these, but just real briefly, if you don\'t know a lot about music and instrumentation, you can just restart with a simple prompt and see what it gives you. You can also use images to influence the outcome and I\'m going to show you a few examples of that as well. If you do have a more intricate knowledge of music and musical styles'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and instrumentation, or you\'re willing to use an LLM to help you do that, you can create very detailed and structured prompts and the prompts are very adherent. The Laleria model allows you to get very specific with what you produce. Obviously the genre, but also the tempo, the instruments used and the'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dynamics throughout the song. As part of your prompt, you can create the actual vocal profile of the singer. So it\'s not completely random. Like do you want a baritone? Do you want the voice to be rich or gravelly or soulful? When it comes to lyrics, of course you can'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt your own or you can let Laleria come up with the lyrics based on the concept that you give it. The other link is also a site for prompting. It goes into a bit more detail and gets into some things that that other one does not. One feature it does mention in this document that Laleria has that I'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'certainly don\'t recall seeing in other models is the ability to timestamp actual changes in style and approach, voices, everything you can change midstream and we\'re going to listen to an example of that as well. To get to Laleria from the OpenArt homepage,'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ll just hover over the audio section and click on create music. You have what they call a quick preview that is only 30 seconds and then you have a full song that can go up to up around 3 minutes. If you just need a 30-second clip of background music or you have something with lyrics that\'s very short, that\'s'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'great. But if your lyrics would naturally go more than 30 seconds, you\'re going to have a problem. And depending on how many lyrics you have, quick clip may garble some of those lyrics or drop some of them out just because of the time constraint. If you have a full song and you\'ve tested the concept to see how it sounds with quick'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clip, then you can click over to full song and it will generate the entire thing. In both cases, you\'ve got the ability to add images of characters or your worlds or anything you\'ve created here at OpenArt. We\'ll look at that later. Here\'s the prompt area. We\'ll talk about how that\'s different in a moment. And here you have your controls.'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you\'re doing an instrumental, you can just turn that on and then it won\'t generate lyrics. When you have quick clip chosen, you can either go auto mode all the way down with BPM or intensity or you can turn these off and you have more precise control over your speed, how frantic the music is or even what'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'key it\'s in. If you\'re in the full song mode, you have the ability to change the duration all the way up to 3 minutes. Let me give you an idea of the quality that Laleria can produce here. We\'ve got a very simple prompt. Complex seven-part harmonies of a church choir slowly singing with timpani accents between'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'phrases. I\'ve got it in the quick clip mode because I\'ve only got two lines here. Laleria is now on OpenArt and I say that twice. I leave everything in auto mode and here\'s what it gave me. &gt;&gt; [singing]'

